INFORMACOES-ADICIONAIS.DESCRICAO-INFORMACOES-ADICIONAIS-INGLES:
In this paper we give a resume of the correlation concept that underlies the models for credit risk measurement, for the rating of structured products, for the pricing of (tranches of) structured products, and for Basel II capital charges. We discuss how securitization has changed the risk characteristics of the credit portfolios and enter into the requirements of transparent and liquid credit indices for the credit portfolio management and for the further development of the securitization market. To capture the evolution in the financial and economic environment (for instance, reflected in the changing risk characteristics) we formulate the basis concepts of a dynamic credit portfolio management framework, that would build further on the common static Rating Based risk methods. 

PS This paper is a very important one as it presents the framework in whcih the securitization activity needs to be managed using risk systems based on the gaussian copula framework. It is my most important work. It shows several important points:

a) the Basel framework of static regulatory capital is simply incorrect;
b) the correlation used by the rating agencies before the credit crunch (for securitization instruments) was far too low. However it points out to a referrence of Fitch for CDOs of ABSs (CDO squared) in which the correlation to be used was around 65%, much higher than was conventional to use bvy market practicioners.
c) the correlation used in risk systems was also very low;
d) given that the process underlying market developments is not a gaussian and as we prove elsewhere, one in practice, can not use Levy-like distributions, one needs to come up with ideas from 'just in time' (Kanban) systems to be able to manage portfolios of securitization and bring the activity back;
e) additionally one needs the standardised credit indices traded in exchanges with standardised and tarnsparent pricing algorithms.

